Here's an example of how to create a simple search bar using PHP. We'll be using HTML, CSS, and PHP for this example.

**index.php**
```php
<?php
// Check if the form has been submitted
if (isset($_POST['search'])) {
    // Get the search query from the form input
    $searchQuery = $_POST['search'];

    // Connect to the database ( replace with your own database credentials )
    $conn = mysqli_connect("localhost", "username", "password", "database");

    if ($conn) {
        // SQL query to search for data in a table called 'items'
        $sql = "SELECT * FROM items WHERE name LIKE '%$searchQuery%' OR description LIKE '%$searchQuery%'";
        $result = mysqli_query($conn, $sql);

        if (mysqli_num_rows($result) > 0) {
            // Display the search results
            while ($row = mysqli_fetch_assoc($result)) {
                echo '<div class="search-result">';
                echo '<h2>' . $row['name'] . '</h2>';
                echo '<p>' . $row['description'] . '</p>';
                echo '</div>';
            }
        } else {
            // Display a message if no results are found
            echo 'No results found.';
        }

        // Close the database connection
        mysqli_close($conn);
    } else {
        // Display an error message if the database connection fails
        echo 'Error: Unable to connect to database.';
    }
}
?>

<!-- HTML form for search bar -->
<form action="<?php $_SERVER['PHP_SELF']; ?>" method="post">
    <input type="text" name="search" placeholder="Search...">
    <button type="submit">Search</button>
</form>

<!-- Style the search results using CSS (in a separate file or inline) -->
<style>
.search-result {
    background-color: #f7f7f7;
    padding: 20px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc;
}

.search-result h2 {
    font-weight: bold;
}
</style>
```
**What this code does:**

*   When the form is submitted, it retrieves the search query from the input field and uses it to search for data in a table called 'items' within the database.
*   It then displays the search results as HTML elements with a title and description.
*   If no results are found, it displays a message indicating that.

**Note:** This code is using MySQLi functions (mysqli\_connect, mysqli\_query, etc.) to interact with your database. Be sure to replace `"localhost"`, `"username"`, `"password"`, and `"database"` with your own database credentials.

**Also note:**

*   SQL injection is prevented here by using parameterized queries. The search query is not directly inserted into the SQL statement.
*   This example assumes a simple search functionality where all matches are displayed as separate items in the result list.

